OK. Let's try this another way:

Consider a user with a fresh linux install - wide eyed and full of
intent. Let's call this user &quot;Bob&quot;. Bob's system python install is
2.5.x. His old Linux used to run 2.4.4... but that was more than a year
ago and time marches on for Bob.

He downloads the Plone 3.x package and runs the unified installer.
Everything is a piece of cake. The installer is a work of art - the
instructions are clear, the system already looks great. Bob has a lovely
contained install at /opt/Plone-3.x and Bob is happy. He installs some
excellent products from plone.org, but he decides it's time to
customise. Archetypes is clearly the way to go. . . and ArchGenXML + UML
are the way to do that.

What does Bob do to get these tools working on his box? If he zaps
python 2.5.x, his boss will tie him to a pillar outside the building and
have him publicly thrashed. Bob doesn't like that idea at all. Not
publicly, anyway. Bob is shy. What is Bob to do?

P.

